04562nam a22006615i 9780520385924DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021007048  a97805203859247 a10.1525/97805203859242doi  a(DE-B1597)613419  a(OCoLC)1320852401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aN7168b.S65 2022 7aART0151102bisacsh04a709.561 09042231 aSmith, Sarah-Neel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMetrics of Modernity :bArt and Development in Postwar Turkey /cSarah-Neel Smith. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Art and Development: A New Framework for Postwar Art -- t1. The Semiperipheral Art Gallery: Gallery Maya, Istanbul -- t2. Democratic Abstractions: Bülent Ecevit on Art and Politics -- t3. “The First Coup in the Turkish Art World”: The Developing Turkey Competition of 1954 / -- t4. The Artist as Agent of Development: Füreya Koral between Turkey and the United States -- tConclusion. Building Istanbul Modern: Art and Development in a Twenty-First-Century Museum -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this vivid portrait of the art world of 1950s Turkey, Sarah-Neel Smith offers a new framework for analyzing global modernisms of the twentieth century: economic development. After World War II, a cohort of influential Turkish modernists built a new art scene in Istanbul and Ankara. The entrepreneurial female gallerist Adalet Cimcoz, the art critic (and future prime minister) Bülent Ecevit, and artists like Aliye Berger, Füreya Koral, and Bedri Rahmi Eyüboğlu were not only focused on aesthetics. On the canvas, in criticism, and in the gallery, these cultural pioneers also grappled with economic questions—attempting to transform their country from a “developing nation” into a major player in the global markets of the postwar period. Smith’s book publishes landmark works of Turkish modernism for the first time, along with an innovative array of sources—from gossip columns to economic theory—to reveal the art world as a key site for the articulation of Turkish nationhood at midcentury.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArt, Moderny20th century. 0aArt, Turkishy20th century. 0aEconomic developmentzTurkeyy20th century. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2022z9783110992809oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107664930 cprintz978052038341840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520385924?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520385924423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520385924/original  a978-3-11-076649-3  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099281-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2022  aZDB-23-DPKb2022  aZDB-23-UCY